The entire refrigeration system has the capacity to hold 20,000 pounds of anhydrous ammonia in a closed loop system.

Under a separate process, anhydrous ammonia 1,200 pounds maximum inventory is used in a Selective Catalytic Reduction (SCR) system to control nitrogen oxides (NOX) emissions from a one Mega Watt natural gas fired turbine. The ammonia is stored in an ASME-rated Pressure Vessel.  This process utilizes anhydrous ammonia in the capacity of a SCR for the Best Available Control Technology (BACT). The SCR system reduces NOX emissions by injecting ammonia into the exhaust gas stream upstream of a catalyst matrix. Nitrogen oxides, ammonia, and oxygen react on the surface of the catalyst to form nitrogen and water. The catalyst is comprised of a noble metal and works within a high temperature range for proper operations (800A° F to 1100A°F). As such, the control efficiency of the SCR system is reducing NOX emissions to about 90 percent.  As described above, this system is offline. 

1.3 Summary of the General Accidental Release Prevention Program and Chemical Specific Prevention Steps

Accidental Release Prevention Program
The design of the Refrigeration & SCR systems along with the implementation of the Cal/ARP Level III Prevention Program (Process Safety Management or PSM) is specifically intended to provide assurance that the risks associated with ammonia are effectively managed.  Gill's Onions developed the facility Process Safety Management (PSM) Program pursuant to Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) guidelines (i.e., 8 CCR A5189).  Gill's Onions first implemented the PSM program on June 18, 1999.  The elements of the Prevention Program are intended to be integrated with the daily and ongoing functions of the facility, and to integrate with other safety programs to th

e extent possible. The programs implemented by Gills Onions should enable the facility to prevent an occurrence and minimize the consequences of a release of Anhydrous Ammonia.  Compliance with RMP, PSM and Cal/ARP comprehensive program ensures the integrity of the Processes that handle flammable or toxic materials. The objectives of the regulation(s) are specifically to prevent unwanted releases of hazardous chemicals. To control these types of hazards, Gills Onions has developed the necessary expertise, experiences, judgment and proactive initiative within their workforce to properly implement and maintain an effective Prevention Program. 

The twelve elements that make up the Prevention Program 3 (PSM) are:
1.   Process Safety Information;
2.   Process Hazard Analysis (PHA);
3.   Operating Procedures;
4.   Training;
5.   Mechanical Integrity;
6.   Management of Change;
7.   Pre-Startup Review;
8.   Compliance Audits;
9.   Incident Investigation;
10. Employee Participation;
11. Hot Work Permit; and,
12. Contractors
 


Chemical-Specific Prevention Steps
In addition to implementation of the RMP Prevention Program Level 3 elements, Gills Onions has implemented specific safety features for the prevention, detection and control of releases of regulated (and other) substances at the facility. The following are some of the control and detection equipment located in and around the facility to minimize the risk of an accident involving ammonia at the Gills Onions Facility:  

1.	Traffic around ammonia equipment (refrigeration and SCR) is minimized with facility design; barriers, and signs.
2.	The facility is protected from fire by an independent fire suppression system. 
3.	Sensitive areas have signage; and are fenced
4.	Staff maintains housekeeping of the facility according to Food Safety Protocols on a day-to-day basis.
5.	The Refrigeration Plant Operator makes daily rounds using checklist and is on call.  
6.	The Plant has an established forma

ding Facility Policy has been adopted.  Plant employees are to implement hazard communications, provide for the safety of visitors and report to the established Evacuation Staging Area(s) for a head count.  Emergency response is coordinated with the City of Oxnard Fire/CUPA.  The Refrigeration Plant Operator and/or other Management would be available to support the Fire Department as technical resources.  The facility has communicated with Oxnard Fire/CUPA to be included in the Oxnard Community Emergency Plan.     

The ERP is designed to be applicable to any type of emergency that may affect Gill's Onions and based on the concept that the elements of emergency response are similar, regardless of the hazard. The ERP comprises the following sections:

1. Agency Interface and Response Planning;
2. Public and Agency Notification;
3. Emergency Medical Care;
4. Emergency Response Actions;
5. Emergency Equipment;
6. Emergency Response Training;
7. Incident Command System; and
8. Plan Review and Update.

Gill's Onions emergency response procedures serve as a guide for emergency control staff, company personnel, emergency assistance groups and law enforcement agencies that may be called upon to participate in controlling an emergency within the facility and surrounding areas. These procedures include employee notification of emergencies and evacuation procedures for emergency situations.  The facility is equipped with windsocks to help determine safe evacuation routes and staging areas.

1.6 Planned Changes to Improve Safety

The primary mechanisms to identify and plan safety improvements include (but are not limited to):
1.	Process Hazard Analysis revalidation/update;
2.	Compliance Audits;
3.	Routine inspections, tests & maintenance (Mechanical Integrity Program);
4.	IIAR Bulletin 109 Inspections (IIAR minimum safety criteria for the safe operation of ammonia refrigeration process);
5.	Gills Onions Internal Inspection Protocols

